## Tax Considerations

### Worst Case (Pension + CPP Only — $62,125)

Approximate federal tax on $62,125 (2025 brackets, before credits):
- 15% on ~$57,375 = $8,606
- 20.5% on ~$4,750 = $974
- **≈ $9,580 federal** + provincial tax + provincial credits

Net worst case after-tax: **≈ $48,000–$52,000/year** depending on province.

### Target Scenario ($200,000 — Mixed Pension + Consulting)

At $200,000 total income:
- Federal marginal rate hits 33% above $246,752; 29% above $155,625
- Most consulting income taxed at **26–29% federal marginal rate**
- Provincial tax adds 10–17% depending on province
- **Combined marginal rate at $200K ≈ 43–53%**

> **Action:** Model the tax split between T4 pension income and T4A/self-employment consulting income. Consulting expenses can reduce net business income. If not already incorporated, assess whether a Stealth EA corporation still makes sense post-retirement.

### Partial Year 2026

In 2026 you will have ~8 months of full consulting income (Jan–Aug) + 4 months of pension + partial CPP. This may result in the highest-income tax year of your retirement transition. Consider:
- Maximizing RRSP contributions before retirement if room exists
- Timing large deductible business expenses before September
- Discussing installment payment obligations for 2026 with an accountant

